==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hemisphere
<hw>Hem"i*sphere</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>hemisphaerium</ets>, Gr. <?/; <?/ half = <?/ sphere: cf. F.
<ets>h⟦eacute⟧misph⟦egrave⟧re</ets>. See <er>Hemi-</er>, and
<er>Sphere</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A half sphere; one half of a
sphere or globe, when divided by a plane passing through its
center.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Half of the terrestrial globe, or a projection of
the same in a map or picture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The people who inhabit a hemisphere.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He died . . . mourned by a <qex>hemisphere</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J.
P. Peters.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cerebral hemispheres</b></col>. <fld>(Anat.)</fld>
<cd>See <er>Brain</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Magdeburg hemispheres</b></col>
<fld>(Physics)</fld>, <cd>two hemispherical cups forming, when placed
together, a cavity from which the air can be withdrawn by an air pump;
-- used to illustrate the pressure of the air. So called because
invented by Otto von Guericke at <etsep>Magdeburg</etsep>.</cd></cs></p>

<p><ent>Hemispherical</ent>⟦br⟧
